Section: introduction
Original: {{c1::The two charts below illustrate the changes in proportion of the average household expenditures over 6 decades from 1950 to 2010.}}
Improved: {{c2::The two charts illustrate the changes in the distribution of average household expenditures across major categories from 1950 to 2010. The data reveals a significant shift in spending patterns, with a notable decrease in expenditure on housing and a corresponding increase in spending on food, while other categories remained relatively stable.}}

Section: overview
Original: {{c1::The most significant changes can be seen where the average household spends significantly less on housing and more on food over the decades. Meanwhile, the amount of money spent on transportation had also slightly increased. Whereas the proportions of spending on other categories had stayed relatively the same over the course of the decades.}}
Improved: {{c2::Overall, the charts show a dramatic decrease in the proportion of household expenditure allocated to housing and a substantial increase in spending on food between 1950 and 2010. Expenditure on transportation also rose moderately, while spending on other categories remained relatively constant.}}

Section: body paragraph 1
Original: {{c1::Looking at the details of the charts, the expenditures of the average families on housing had decreased by one third of it's original portion of 72 percent. While food portion of the spending had increased by one third of its original portion of 11 percent, a slight increase of spending by 10 percent on transportation can also be seen by the families over the years.}}
Improved: {{c2::A detailed analysis reveals that housing expenditure decreased by approximately one-third from its initial 72% share, while the proportion allocated to food increased by one-third from its original 11%. Transportation costs also saw a modest 10% increase over the period.}}

Section: body paragraph 2
Original: {{c1::While the housing, food and portion had undergone changes, the chart shows that the other categories like health care, education has stayed relatively unchanged.}}
Improved: {{c2::In contrast to the significant changes in housing and food expenditures, the remaining categories, including healthcare and education, showed relatively little change in their share of total household spending throughout the period. Further detailed analysis would be required to confirm the exact percentage changes in these areas.}}
